SH(1)                            User Commands                           SH(1)

NAME
       sh - LikeOS-64 command interpreter

SYNOPSIS
       sh

DESCRIPTION
       sh  is  the  default  interactive command interpreter for LikeOS-64.  It
       reads commands from  standard  input,  parses  them,  and  executes  the
       corresponding  programs.   It supports pipelines, I/O redirection, here-
       documents, command chaining, aliases, command history, and job control.

       sh is not a POSIX shell.  It does not support  shell  scripting  (loops,
       conditionals,  functions),  variable  expansion,  globbing, or arithmetic
       expansion.  It is designed as a lightweight interactive command line  for
       the LikeOS-64 operating system.

INVOCATION
       sh  is  normally started automatically by the system as the login shell.
       It sets PATH to /bin:/usr/local/bin before entering the interactive read-
       eval-execute loop.

PROMPT
       The prompt displays the current working directory followed by " # ":

              /bin # _

       If the current directory is the root, the prompt is simply:

              / # _

QUOTING
       Single quotes preserve the literal value of all characters  within  the
       quotes.  No escape sequences are recognized inside single quotes.

       Double  quotes  preserve  the literal value of all characters except for
       backslash (\), which can be used to escape the next character.

       A backslash (\) outside of quotes escapes the next character,  including
       the pipe character (\|) for a literal pipe.

OPERATORS
       The following operators are supported:

   Pipelines
       command1 | command2
              Connect  stdout  of  command1  to  stdin of command2.  Multiple
              pipes can be chained.

       command1 |& command2
              Connect both stdout and stderr of command1 to stdin of command2.

   I/O Redirection
       command > file
              Redirect stdout to file (overwrite).

       command >> file
              Redirect stdout to file (append).

       command < file
              Redirect stdin from file.

       command 2> file
              Redirect stderr to file (overwrite).

       command 2>> file
              Redirect stderr to file (append).

       command 2>&1
              Redirect stderr to stdout.

       command &> file
              Redirect both stdout and stderr to file (overwrite).

       command &>> file
              Redirect both stdout and stderr to file (append).

       command >& file
              Same as &> (older form).

       command <> file
              Open file for read/write on stdin.

       command >| file
              Force overwrite even with noclobber (override).

   Here-Documents
       command << DELIMITER
              Read input lines until a line containing only DELIMITER is  seen.
              The collected text is fed to the command's stdin.

   Here-Strings
       command <<< word
              Feed  the  single  word  (or  quoted string) directly to the
              command's stdin.

   Command Lists
       command1 ; command2
              Execute command1, then execute command2.

       command1 && command2
              Execute command2 only if command1 succeeds (exit status 0).

       command1 || command2
              Execute command2 only if command1 fails (non-zero exit status).

   Background Execution
       command &
              Run command in the background without waiting for it to complete.

BUILT-IN COMMANDS
       cd [dir]
              Change  the  current  working directory to dir.  If dir is omitted,
              change to the directory specified by the HOME environment variable,
              or / if HOME is not set.

       alias [-p] [name[=value] ...]
              With  no  arguments  or  with -p, print all defined aliases in the
              form alias name='value'.  With arguments, define  aliases  so  that
              name is expanded to value before command execution.

              Aliases  are expanded in pipelines, so an alias for a multi-word
              command works correctly even when piped.

       unalias [-a] name ...
              Remove each name from the list of defined aliases.  With -a, remove
              all alias definitions.

       export [-fnp] [name[=value] ...]
              Mark  each  name  to  be  passed  to  child  processes  in   the
              environment.

              -f     Not implemented (reserved for functions).

              -n     Remove  the  export  property  from each name (unset the
                     variable).

              -p     Display all exported variables.

              With no arguments, list all exported variables.

       history [-cdanrwsp]
              Display or manipulate the command history list.

              -c     Clear the history list.

              -d offset
                     Delete the history entry at position offset.

              -a     Append new history lines to the history file.

              -n     Read history lines not already read from the history file.

              -r     Read the history file and append its contents to the history
                     list.

              -w     Write the current history to the history file.

              -s arg ...
                     Append args to the history list as a single entry.

              -p arg ...
                     Perform history substitution on each arg and display the
                     result.

              With no arguments, display the history list with line numbers.

       time [-p] pipeline
              Execute  pipeline and print a summary of the real time elapsed and
              the user and system time consumed.

              -p     Use the POSIX output format.

       help   Display a summary of built-in commands, operators, external
              commands, and keyboard shortcuts.

       exit [N]
              Exit the shell with status N.  If N is omitted, exit with the
              status of the last command executed.

KEYBOARD SHORTCUTS
       Ctrl+C Interrupt the currently running foreground process by sending
              SIGINT.

       Ctrl+D Print a debug dump of the shell's internal state.

ENVIRONMENT
       PATH   Colon-separated list of directories to search for external
              commands.  Defaults to /bin:/usr/local/bin.

       HOME   The home directory, used by cd when invoked without arguments.

EXTERNAL COMMANDS
       The following external commands are available in /bin:

              cat clear cp cut date df dmesg du echo env false file find free
              grep halt head hexdump kill less ls man mkdir more mv poweroff
              printf ps pwd reboot rm rmdir shutdown sleep sort stat strings
              tail time top touch tr true uname uniq uptime wc which yes

       Additional programs are in /usr/local/bin:

              hello memstat progerr testlibc testmem teststress tests

EXIT STATUS
       The shell returns the exit status of the last command executed, or the
       value specified by the exit built-in.

NOTES
       This shell does not support:

       o  Shell scripting (for, while, until, if/then/else, case/esac)
       o  Shell functions
       o  Variable expansion ($VAR, ${VAR}, $(...), `...`)
       o  Arithmetic expansion ($((...)))
       o  Filename globbing (*, ?, [...])
       o  Tilde expansion (~)
       o  Brace expansion ({a,b,c})
       o  Process substitution (<(...), >(...))
       o  Signal trapping (trap)
       o  Startup files (.profile, .bashrc)

       For a fully featured POSIX shell, see bash(1) if available.

AUTHORS
